3243,IssuesEvent,2015-11-16 10:03:18+00:00,11147494,JustGlowing/minisom,5238619,remidomingues,,,opened,Computation of the MID for the neurons on the sides,[],[],0,"Hi,

I'm using the interneuron distance matrix computed by the function distance_map, and saw in the comments of the function that the distance returned should be the normalized mean.

Yet, I don't see the computation of the mean of the distances. It seems that the code only sums up distances and then apply normalization. By doing so, the neurons located on the sides and having thus only 3 neighbors will have a lower distance (less additions and no averaging).

- Shouldn't we count the number of neighbors and divide the distance by this number?
- Shouldn't we ignore the distance between the neuron and itself in this computation?

To illustrate this, I attach a MID matrix that shows smaller (darker) distances on the sides, and the corresponding neural network in 2D (dimensionality reduction provided by MDS from scikit-learn).

![som_mid_qe 0 96](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5238619/11179109/6f140d6e-8c51-11e5-9983-5d2d746ebdb9.png)

![som2d_grid true_data false_qe 0 96](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5238619/11179111/7428220e-8c51-11e5-9ce4-3485b572b530.png)

After averaging, I obtain the following MID matrix:
![som_mid_qe 0 96](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5238619/11179126/8f2cd6d0-8c51-11e5-9442-6d37bbc78dd6.png)


",{},{}
