3426,IssuesEvent,2018-07-11 18:06:59+00:00,69090889,hardbyte/python-can,3647996,christiansandberg,,,closed,Vector unconnected interface handling,[],[],1,"https://github.com/hardbyte/python-can/blob/6d0f4a66d121e86d2c8c707ce11546822a0ca1d2/can/interfaces/vector/canlib.py#L102-L104

If the application config is okay but the interface that channel is associated to is disconnected, xlGetChannelIndex returns a negative number and `mask = 1 << idx` fails with `ValueError: negative shift count`.

In 2.1.0, it died here: https://github.com/hardbyte/python-can/blob/338d21191ef89e9cb515eae80d9d945d12028477/can/interfaces/vector/canlib.py#L83-L85
with `can.interfaces.vector.exceptions.VectorError: XL_ERR_WRONG_PARAMETER`, presumably as a result of passing the negative self.mask to the Vector API.

Neither is a particularly graceful way of handling the error. Does their API documentation say what's supposed to happen when the interface isn't there? Is it possible to test that and raise a nicer exception?",{},{}
