4468,IssuesEvent,2016-02-23 05:59:30+00:00,4053456,martinblech/xmltodict,78768,martinblech,,,closed,postprocessor doesn't have effect on attributes?,[],[],0,"It seems like postprocessor doesn't run on attributes.

```
>>> def postprocessor(path, key, value):
...	try:
...		return key, int(value)
...	except (ValueError, TypeError):
...		return key, value
>>> doc=""""""<mydoc has=""an attribute"" version=2><and><many>elements</many><many>more elements</many><numbers>2</numbers></and></mydoc>""""""
>>> json.dumps(xmltodict.parse(doc))
'{""mydoc"": {""@has"": ""an attribute"", ""@version"": ""2"", ""and"": {""many"": [""elements"", ""more elements""], ""numbers"": ""2""}}}'
>>> json.dumps(xmltodict.parse(doc, postprocessor=postprocessor))
'{""mydoc"": {""@has"": ""an attribute"", ""@version"": ""2"", ""and"": {""many"": [""elements"", ""more elements""], ""numbers"": 2}}}'

```

As of here, `@version` should be converted integer but didn't, while `numbers` converted as integer 2.

Is there other method to run postprocessor on attributes?",{},{}
