6126,IssuesEvent,2017-10-10 20:28:05+00:00,76801332,RobinNil/file_read_backwards,9019561,hansgoldman,,,opened,Feature Request: Read Line Method,[],[],0,"* file_read_backwards version: 1.2.1
* Python version: 3.5.2
* Operating System: Windows Server 2012 R2

### Description

I was trying to read the 2nd to last line from multiple files which is why I installed file_read_backwards. It works great if you want to iterate over a complete file, but if you just want the last line then the code starts getting more complicated than it needs to be. It would be great to have a readLine() method that would call the iterator's next value (from a code-readability standpoint).

### What I Did

```
I used the following code to accomplish what I wanted:
with file_read_backwards.FileReadBackwards(filePath) as fileHandle:
        lineIterator = iter(fileHandle)

        lineIterator.next()         # Get last line of file
        line = lineIterator.next()  # Get 2nd to last line of file
```
Instead, it would be amazing to do the following:
with file_read_backwards.FileReadBackwards(filePath) as fileHandle:
        fileHandle.readLine()          # Get last line of file
        line = fileHandle.readLine()   # Get 2nd to last line of file
```

The library worked great other than that. Thanks!!!",{},{}
