7878,IssuesEvent,2017-02-06 13:10:59+00:00,744916,gem/oq-engine,2463856,micheles,316546,gem,opened,Remove the two-phase constraint on the event based calculators,"[{'id': 262430947, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/gem/oq-engine/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '009800', 'default': True}]","[{'login': 'micheles', 'id': 2463856, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/2463856?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/micheles', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/micheles/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"Right now the event based calculators have a serious architectural constraint: they are split in two sequential phase, 1) rupture generation and 2) gmf generation.

This is a big problem for large computations and causes the following issues.

a) we may run out of memory when storing the ruptures at the end of phase 1)
b) the calculation became ultra-slow when saving and then reading the ruptures between phases 1) and 2)
c) rabbitmq may fail when transferring the ruptures at the beginning of phase 2)

The solution is to generate the ruptures and use them within the same task (single phase calculation). This is way the UCERF risk calculator is possible. However, the present UCERF risk calculator parallelizes by source model branch: this means that when there is a single branch it will use a single core, i.e. it is practically useless.

Why we have the two-phase architecture? Because we lack a *centralized provider of event IDs*. Currently in phase 1) we generate bogus event IDs which are replaced by sequential event IDs only after the events are stored. In order to avoid storing the events or keeping them in memory all at once, we need to set the event IDs before, in the workers. Thus we need a function `get_seq_ids(num_events)` able to return an array of sequential IDs, such that each worker gets different IDs. We need an implementation of `get_seq_ids(num_events)` working on a single machine (here shared memory can be used to keep of counter of events) and an implementation working on a cluster of machines (here we can use the dbserver as mediator).",{},{}
