8018,IssuesEvent,2016-02-17 22:40:33+00:00,6670942,boto/botocore,11759196,carl0FF,327752,boto,closed,What would be the implications of disabling validation in serialization?,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/botocore/labels/closing-soon-if-no-response', 'name': 'closing-soon-if-no-response', 'color': '5319e7'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/botocore/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],2,"In an application that uses boto to massively insert to DynamoDB we've been able to observe how a significant amount of CPU time is dedicated to serialization and a part of it is dedicated parameter validation. 

Disabling validation (through forcing ``include_validation=False`` in ``create_serializer()`` at serialize.py) leads to a ~23% performance increase. 

Now, the question is: **how (un)safe would be to disable validation in a production system?**

python 2.7 
Amazon Linux AMI 2015.09
botocore 1.3.15
",{},{}
8064,IssuesEvent,2017-06-12 12:25:23+00:00,68928471,inspirehep/inspire-schemas,381280,jacquerie,356664,inspirehep,opened,experiments: institution -> institutions,[],[],0,"An Experiment record can have multiple associated institutions. For example: https://inspirehep.net/record/1228417/export/xme

The schema currently only allows for one: https://github.com/inspirehep/inspire-schemas/blob/006537d31a1267959ac7003805aecdb04359434a/inspire_schemas/records/experiments.yml#L249-L268.

So `institution` must be changed to to an array called `institutions` in order to accomodate them.",{},{}
