8810,IssuesEvent,2015-07-29 23:58:18+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,136574,kbourgoin,779641,Parsely,opened,Leaderless Topics Shouldn't Break KafkaClient,[],[],0,"In [broker.py](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/12f522870a32198f70a92ce543950c88b9f75565/pykafka/broker.py#L264-L266), if a topic has a missing partition leader, then [cluster initialization](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/12f522870a32198f70a92ce543950c88b9f75565/pykafka/cluster.py#L154-L156) fails, raising an Exception. This behavior is no good. We should warn, but really only throw the exception if someone goes to read/write that topic/partition.

Also, we should add the topic/partition to those log messages, because it's pretty unhelpful right now.",{},{}
8818,IssuesEvent,2015-05-12 05:23:05+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,482743,benauthor,779641,Parsely,opened,balanced consumers not balancing nicely,[],[],0,"First: kudos on a fine effort here. Been following along for a little while and I look forward to the next release. :beers: 

I tried out the balancedconsumer this evening and while it consumes, the balancing appears not to work as I'd expect (expectations on the matter having been set by the Java high level consumer). Here's my dumb little consumer https://github.com/benauthor/storm-env/blob/master/consumers/pykafka-balanced.py. I've got a dumb little producer producing round-robin to a topic of say 6 partitions.

Expected behavior:
- Start consumer A on topic & group. It consumes messages from all 6 partitions.
- Start consumer B on topic & group. B gets 3 partitions, and A is rebalanced to 3.
- Kill consumer B. A rebalanced again and consumes all 6 partitions.

Observed:
- Start consumer A on topic & group. It consume messages from all 6 partitions.
- Start consumer B on topic & group. B gets 3 partitions. A stalls, stops consuming messages.
- Kill consumer B. A still stalled, consuming no messages. (Alternatively, kill consumer A. B continues to consume only 3 partitions).

Zookeeper log during startup of A and then B:

```
(A starts here)

[2015-05-12 05:13:24,893] INFO Accepted socket connection from /127.0.0.1:42695 (org.apache.zookeeper.server.NIOServerCnxnFactory)
[2015-05-12 05:13:24,893] INFO Client attempting to establish new session at /127.0.0.1:42695 (org.apache.zookeeper.server.ZooKeeperServer)
[2015-05-12 05:13:24,895] INFO Established session 0x14d464a7c860023 with negotiated timeout 6000 for client /127.0.0.1:42695 (org.apache.zookeeper.server.ZooKeeperServer)

(B starts here)

[2015-05-12 05:13:45,580] INFO Accepted socket connection from /127.0.0.1:42699 (org.apache.zookeeper.server.NIOServerCnxnFactory)
[2015-05-12 05:13:45,580] INFO Client attempting to establish new session at /127.0.0.1:42699 (org.apache.zookeeper.server.ZooKeeperServer)
[2015-05-12 05:13:45,585] INFO Established session 0x14d464a7c860024 with negotiated timeout 6000 for client /127.0.0.1:42699 (org.apache.zookeeper.server.ZooKeeperServer)
[2015-05-12 05:13:45,599] INFO Got user-level KeeperException when processing sessionid:0x14d464a7c860024 type:create cxid:0xb zxid:0x282 txntype:-1 reqpath:n/a Error Path:/consumers/mygroup/owners/test2/0-1 Error:KeeperErrorCode = NodeExists for /consumers/mygroup/owners/test2/0-1 (org.apache.zookeeper.server.PrepRequestProcessor)
[2015-05-12 05:13:45,603] INFO Got user-level KeeperException when processing sessionid:0x14d464a7c860024 type:create cxid:0xf zxid:0x283 txntype:-1 reqpath:n/a Error Path:/consumers/mygroup/owners/test2/0-1 Error:KeeperErrorCode = NodeExists for /consumers/mygroup/owners/test2/0-1 (org.apache.zookeeper.server.PrepRequestProcessor)
```

Nothing much of interest in kafka log.

I was on *one occasion* able to get two consumers both consuming their partitions simultanously by starting them in close succession. But killing one produced a similar result to that described above.",{},{}
