8857,IssuesEvent,2018-06-04 07:46:19+00:00,1811242,Simplistix/testfixtures,331955,ziima,809412,Simplistix,opened,Possibility to ignore other warnings in ShouldWarn,[],[],0,"I use `ShouldWarn` from time to time, but I found it very difficult to use in cases, when I want to check only one of several warnings that happen to occur.

Consider case:
```python
def deprecated_utility():
    warnings.warn(""This utility is deprecated."", DeprecationWarning)

def deprecated_function():
    warnings.warn(""This function is deprecated."", DeprecationWarning)
    deprecated_utilitiy()

with ShouldWarn(DeprecationWarning(""This function is deprecated."")):
    deprecated_function()
```
This fails because there are two warnings raised instead of only one. I really don't care about the other one, but I only want to check the one I defined. I can bypass that by capturing, but it cumbersome and may be potentially difficult, since warnings may be dependent on the version of python, third party library etc.

I'd like a simple switch, which would ignore all other warnings accidentally captured by `ShouldWarn`.",{},{}
8858,IssuesEvent,2018-03-28 10:47:38+00:00,1811242,Simplistix/testfixtures,592390,Estartu,809412,Simplistix,opened,Parameter oder changed between 5.4.0 and 6.0.0 with logcapture and mock.patch,[],[],0,"I have a unittest that uses both mock.patch and log_capture decorator. 

    @mock.patch('evmanagement.iter_entry_points')
    @log_capture('evmanagement', level=logging.INFO)
    def test_main_entrypoint_callable(self, mock_iep, logs):
        print mock_iep
        print logs

with textfixtures 5.4.0 it prints 
<MagicMock name='iter_entry_points' id='34698917264'>
No logging captured

with textfixtures 6.0.0 it prints 
No logging captured
<MagicMock name='iter_entry_points' id='34698917776'>

as you can see the parameter order has changed with the update.

",{},{}
