8924,IssuesEvent,2017-12-09 13:58:13+00:00,2494665,fluent/fluent-logger-python,5355666,arcivanov,859518,fluent,opened,Use actual bytesarray/memoryview instead of bytes concatenation,[],[],0,"Bytes concatenation such as this is extremely wasteful and is never a good idea. 

https://github.com/fluent/fluent-logger-python/blob/master/fluent/sender.py#L137
```python
        # buffering
        if self.pendings:
            self.pendings += bytes_
            bytes_ = self.pendings
```

Python has mutable buffers that should be used to ensure that the objects aren't created needlessly putting pressure on GC and wasting CPU with double-copy concatenation.",{},{}
8954,IssuesEvent,2016-01-21 20:31:55+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,2184487,JDWarner,897180,scikit-image,opened,"HOG kwarg 'normalise' does not normalize data, replace it",[],[],0,"When `normalise=True`, HOG operates on the square root of the raw input data. See [this line](https://github.com/scikit-image/scikit-image/blob/master/skimage/feature/_hog.py#L70).

This is a problem because `np.sqrt` is not a normalization. It is a transform of the data. The data is not scaled or guaranteed to have a particular range after it is applied; it's just a square root. What's more, the square root is not defined for all input data.

As a result, users will apply this kwarg thinking it will normalize their data when in fact it may be creating problems (see #1889).

Generally, kwargs should have intuitive names. This one is bad enough I think it should be loudly deprecated in advance of 0.12. 

An acceptable resolution would include:

* Replace `normalise` with something like `transform_sqrt`.
* If this code path is used, check the minimum value of the input array. If it is negative, warn the user their result will have NaNs.",{},{}
