10765,IssuesEvent,2017-12-05 21:46:44+00:00,59868262,aws/chalice,368057,jamesls,2232217,aws,closed,Add UnprocessableEntityError for HTTP status 422,"[{'id': 383737477, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws/chalice/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}]",[],1,"I use HTTP status code 422 for responses like POST when the entity already exists. This is a very common practice. I created a new class for this in my own code, but it would be better directly in Chalice.",{},{}
10771,IssuesEvent,2017-11-15 14:21:44+00:00,59868262,aws/chalice,11985743,gldavis3000,2232217,aws,closed,Bug report: Missing request body,"[{'id': 403474419, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws/chalice/labels/closing-soon-if-no-response', 'name': 'closing-soon-if-no-response', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}]",[],2,"Bug report: I recently got a new computer at my job so I had to reinstall chalice.  After deploying our api with the new version of chalice I noticed that every request body was being stripped out (anything other than GET that has no body of course).  I don't know exactly which part of the chalice process caused this to happen.  All I know is that when I did app.current_request.to_dict() to get the event it contained no '_body' or 'body'.  When I did pip install chalice on my new computer it installed version 1.0.4.  I reverted this back to 1.0.3 then 1.0.2 which both resulted in the stripped body.  When I reverted back to 1.0.1 the body showed up again.  I can continue working now, but I thought you should be aware of this.",{},{}
