12546,IssuesEvent,2016-08-07 17:21:33+00:00,41284151,frictionlessdata/tabulator-py,557395,roll,5912125,frictionlessdata,closed,Encoding and recoding,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/frictionlessdata/tabulator-py/labels/feature', 'name': 'feature', 'color': '159818'}]",[],1,"See https://github.com/openspending/openspending/issues/897

We need the ability to recode a file to utf-8, creating this file as a side effect of a recode processor.

Internally, Tabulator is recoding as utf-8 anyway, as goodtables is. 

I'm not sure exactly the steps required: maybe there are alternatives to having a dedicated processor to produce the output file, but at a high-level view it seems reasonable.

I guess the spec looks something like this:

* input file has some encoding
* recode processor can create an output file, at a passed location, in any desired encoding, with utf-8 as default.",{},{}
12552,IssuesEvent,2017-02-24 17:33:47+00:00,44518409,frictionlessdata/datapackage-py,772616,danfowler,5912125,frictionlessdata,opened,Be clearer about what .validate() does,[],[],0,"It's not clear enough in the README that the `.validate()` method only validates that the descriptor is well formed according to the specification.  I think ""validating a data package"" might imply validating that the data is good too.  We should mention what this does and refer to Good Tables for full validation.  Probably also worth mentioning that retrieving the data will result in a `ValueError` if the data doesn't conform to the type specified in the schema.

https://github.com/frictionlessdata/datapackage-py#validating-a-data-package",{},{}
12568,IssuesEvent,2018-03-29 15:11:33+00:00,50729855,stephenslab/dsc,917985,gaow,5939770,stephenslab,opened,[dscrutils] set seed,[],[],0,"The code below:

```yaml
# Simulate samples from the normal distribution with mean 0 and
# standard deviation 1.
normal: R(x <- rnorm(n,mean = mu,sd = 1))
  mu: R(stats::rnorm(1))
  n: 100
  $data: x
  $true_mean: mu

# Simulate samples from the non-centered t-distribution with 3 degrees
# of freedom.
t: R(x <- mu + rt(n,df = 2))
  mu: R(stats::rnorm(1))
  n: 100
  $data: x
  $true_mean: mu
```

Results in 

```
> dscquery(""first_investigation"",targets=""simulate.mu"")
  DSC simulate simulate.mu
1   1   normal     -1.4318
2   2   normal     -1.4318
3   1        t      0.5664
4   2        t      0.5664
```

But we want `simulate.mu` be the same since they are parameters. That is, we should set a seed to `dscrutils` -- @pcarbo does it make sense?

BTW @pcarbo if we want `mu` be different for every replicate, the only way to achieve it is to use `raw()` instead of `R()`",{},{}
