16496,IssuesEvent,2018-02-18 16:43:49+00:00,43056951,graphql-python/graphene,691952,jkimbo,15002022,graphql-python,closed,How to write nested mutations?,[],[],5,"Is it possible to pass the output of one mutation to another? I would like the `WriteImage` resolver to accept its input image from the `ReadImage` resolver. 
The schema looks like this:

    import SimpleITK as sitk
    import graphene
    from graphql.execution.executors.asyncio import AsyncioExecutor
    
    class Image(graphene.Scalar):
        '''SimpleITK Image Type'''
    
        @staticmethod
        def serialize(Image):
            return Image
    
        @staticmethod
        def parse_literal(node):
            if isinstance(node, sitk.Image):
                return node
    
        @staticmethod
        def parse_value(value):
            return value

    class ReadImage(graphene.Mutation):
        class Input:
            path = graphene.String()
    
        image = Image()
    
        @staticmethod
        async def mutate(cls, args, context, info):
            image = sitk.ReadImage(args.get('path'))
            return ReadImage(image=image)
    
    
    class WriteImage(graphene.Mutation):
        class Input:
            image = Image()
            path = graphene.String()
    
        image = Image()
    
        @staticmethod
        async def mutate(cls, args, context, info):
            image = args.get('image')
            sitk.WriteImage(image, args.get('path'))
            return WriteImage(image=image)
    
    class Query(graphene.ObjectType):
        dummy = graphene.Field(graphene.String)

        async def resolve_dummy(self, args, context, info):
            return 'dummy'

    class Mutation(graphene.ObjectType):
        readImage = ReadImage.Field()
        writeImage = WriteImage.Field()
    
    
    schema = graphene.Schema(
        query=Query,
        mutation=Mutation,
    )
    
    executed = schema.execute(
        """"""
            mutation {
                writeImage(
                    image: {
                        readImage(
                            path: ""/path/to/image.nii""
                        ) {
                            image
                        }
                    },
                    path: ""/Users/kasper/Desktop""
                ) {
                    image
                }
            }
        """""", executor=AsyncioExecutor())

    print(executed.data)
    print(executed.errors)

This outputs 

    >>> None
    >>> [GraphQLError('Argument ""image"" has invalid value ReadImageInput.\nExpected ""ReadImageInput"", found not an object.',)]

What does this error message mean? Why is it `not an object`? How should the schema be structured so that I may use output from one resolver as input to another?

Additional info: Executing the `ReadImage` produces the following output:

    executed = schema.execute(
        """"""
            mutation {
                readImage(
                    path: ""/path/to/image.nii""
                ) {
                    image
                }
            }
        """""", executor=AsyncioExecutor())
    
    print(executed.data)
    print(executed.errors)

    >>> OrderedDict([('readImage', OrderedDict([('image', <SimpleITK.SimpleITK.Image; proxy of <Swig Object of type 'std::vector< itk::simple::Image >::value_type *' at 0x1087b5030> >)]))])
    >>> None",{},{}
16518,IssuesEvent,2017-08-18 17:27:57+00:00,43056951,graphql-python/graphene,787203,phil303,15002022,graphql-python,closed,Getting GeventExecutor and DataLoader to play nicely with each other,[],[],3,"Disclaimer, this could be my misunderstanding how these two things should work together - I'm trying to get `DataLoader` to play nicely with `GeventExecutor` so that I can have requests to different services work in parallel. But I'm noticing that when I include `GeventExecutor` this doesn't happen and is actually breaking up what were originally batch requests via `some_loader.load_many` into individual ones.

My initial call into graphql is via the webob integration:
```python
serve_graphql_request(
    request,
    request.schema,
    executor=GeventExecutor(),
    context_value=GraphQLContext(),
)
```

An example resolver:
```python
class Query(graphene.ObjectType):
    trending_articles = graphene.List(of_type=Article)

    def resolve_trending_articles(self, args, context, info):
        ids = resolvers.get_trending_article_ids()
        return context.article_loader.load_many(ids)
```

And the relevant loader:
```python
class ArticleLoader(DataLoader):
    # article_ids is being set as a one item list for each id in the load_many call
    def batch_load_fn(self, article_ids):
        articles = article_service_client.get_articles(article_ids)
        return Promise.resolve([build_article(article) for article in articles])
```

`load_many` calls into `load` internally which, via the function call in the Promise object [here](https://github.com/syrusakbary/promise/blob/master/promise/dataloader.py#L72), is adding a loader object with the notion of the resolver into a queue. The part that I start to lose the thread on is what happens around [here](https://github.com/syrusakbary/promise/blob/master/promise/dataloader.py#L199). I believe the queue starts being drained but I'm unclear as to why this starts to happen immediately in the case of the GeventExecutor.

Any insight on this?",{},{}
