16878,IssuesEvent,2018-07-22 23:00:33+00:00,1404690,PmagPy/PmagPy,1278789,njarboe,16460206,PmagPy,closed,Problems plotting MagIC 3.0 pole plots with multiple rows in the location table with the same name,"[{'id': 500827042, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw1MDA4MjcwNDI=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/PmagPy/PmagPy/labels/Bug%20-%20Affects%20Features', 'name': 'Bug - Affects Features', 'color': 'b60205', 'default': False}, {'id': 602374836, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw2MDIzNzQ4MzY=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/PmagPy/PmagPy/labels/Bug%20-%20MagIC%202%20--%3E%20MagIC%203', 'name': 'Bug - MagIC 2 --> MagIC 3', 'color': 'b60205', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'moonshoes87', 'id': 1836578, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjE4MzY1Nzg=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/1836578?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/moonshoes87', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/moonshoes87/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",8,"Here is an example of a contribution that is typical for a pole only contribution. It has two locations but four rows in the location table. The ""Guyana Permo-Triassic Dykes"" location is listed only once and should have its pole plotted by make_magic_plots.

The next three rows in the locations table are for the ""La Quinta Formation Lavas"". The first row, with all the sites averaged, and then the normal and reversed poles. I imagine we could use all of the three as plots, but the most important one is the first one that includes both reversed and normal.

Then it would also be nice to have a pole plot that has two points, the ""Guyana Permo-Triassic Dykes"" location and the main ""La Quinta Formation Lavas"".

So using the naming convention following the current one, we would want:
'LO:_' + 'Guyana Permo-Triassic Dykes' + '_POLE_map.' + fmt - The one pole given in the locations table 
'LO:_' + 'La Quinta Formation Lavas' + '_POLE_map.' + fmt - The combined pole. The second row in the table. Can be distinguished from the other ones with the same location name by the fact that the dir_polarity column is empty.

'MC:_' + '12012' + '_POLE_map.' + fmt - The two poles above plotted on the same plot. MC stands for magic contribution.

Then for the ones that have values in the dir_polarity column, One could create those and name them 
'LO:_' + 'La Quinta Formation Lavas' +'_n' +'_POLE_map.' + fmt
'LO:_' + 'La Quinta Formation Lavas' +'_r' +'_POLE_map.' + fmt

depending on the value in the dir_polarity column.

Magic Contribution file:
[magic_contribution_12012.txt](https://github.com/PmagPy/PmagPy/files/2199642/magic_contribution_12012.txt)

locations.txt file:
[locations.txt](https://github.com/PmagPy/PmagPy/files/2199641/locations.txt)

Currently on the pmag server, make_magic_plots uses polemap_magic.py to make this plot from this contribution:
![lo___ty__pole_map](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1278789/42788756-3d277ccc-8916-11e8-9ec2-4b92a52da94c.png)
Which looks empty and has an empty file name.
",{},{}
