17280,IssuesEvent,2016-08-26 09:45:09+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,2418513,aldanor,17565521,pybind,opened,Typed iterators/iterables,[],[],0,"I was thinking, it would be nice to have typed iterators and iterables (kind of like you can have typed numpy arrays), so you can do things like accept arguments of type `iterable_t<MyObject>` which will provide you with appropriate `.begin()` and `.end()`.

In the prototype example below, you can do things like this which is pretty nice (note that we can't directly construct objects of type `Foo` in Python but we can manipulate existing Foo-iterables and send them back to C++):

```python
>>> generate(5)
[Foo(0, 0), Foo(1, 10), Foo(2, 20), Foo(3, 30), Foo(4, 40)]
>>> dump(generate(5))
[ Foo(0, 0) Foo(1, 10) Foo(2, 20) Foo(3, 30) Foo(4, 40) ]
>>> dump(f for f in generate(5) if f.x % 2 == 0)  # pass a lazy iterator
[ Foo(0, 0) Foo(2, 20) Foo(4, 40) ]
```

If this looks good, I could open a PR.

A related improvement would be to relax input object requirements if an input argument of a method is `std::vector<T>`. It should really be a ""sized iterable"" (aka [Sequence](https://docs.python.org/3/library/collections.abc.html#collections.abc.Sequence)) instead of a list which is unnecesarily restrictive.

Here's the C++ code for the example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>

namespace py = pybind11;

template<typename T> class iterator_t : public py::iterator {
public:
    using iterator::iterator;

    // cheap/lazy way of doing this as it could be done in advance(), 
    // but then py::iterator needs to be changed
    auto operator*() const {
        return this->iterator::operator*().cast<T>();
    }
};

template<typename T> class iterable_t : public py::iterable {
public:
    using iterable::iterable;

    iterator_t<T> begin() { return {PyObject_GetIter(ptr()), false}; }
    iterator_t<T> end() { return {nullptr, false}; }
};

struct Foo {
    int x;
    int y;

    Foo(int x, int y) : x{x}, y{y} {}

    std::string to_string() const {
        return std::string(""Foo("") + std::to_string(x) + "", "" +
            std::to_string(y) + "")"";
    }
};

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(test_iter) {
    py::module m(""test_iter"");

    py::class_<Foo>(m, ""Foo"")
        .def(py::init<int, int>())
        .def_property_readonly(""x"", [](const Foo& v) { return v.x; })
        .def_property_readonly(""y"", [](const Foo& v) { return v.y; })
        .def(""__str__"", [](const Foo& v) { return v.to_string(); })
        .def(""__repr__"", [](const Foo& v) { return v.to_string(); });

    m.def(""generate"", [](int n) {  // this could actually return an iterator as well
        std::vector<Foo> data;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
            data.emplace_back(i, i * 10);
        return data;
    });

    m.def(""dump"", [](iterable_t<Foo> x) {
        std::cout << ""["";
        for (auto v : x)
            std::cout << "" "" << v.to_string();
        std::cout << "" ]"" << std::endl;
    });

    return m.ptr();
}
```",{},{}
