18166,IssuesEvent,2017-06-06 21:43:38+00:00,985638,django-helpdesk/django-helpdesk,17169553,mrkiwi-nz,22762644,django-helpdesk,opened,default assigned_to,[],[],0,"## Feature Request
As far as i can tell, there are no settings to handle this situation;
* A mailbox is set up to receive bounced email messages from automated systems
* These bounces should **never** be replied to - the bounce is there because the original sender is not contactable and the reason is somewhere in the message (ie over quota, bad MX, no mailbox at that address, temporary routing failure)
* A queue in django-helpdesk is created and configured to watch this mailbox - the tickets created by the emails **should** be automatically assigned to one person and an email sent to them, and as above, should **not** generate the email acknowledging the creation of the ticket

We have the same situation for queues that monitor application errors, printer faults, system alerts etc etc - all have the same attributes in that the owner/submitter of the ticket is not a real person and should not be replied to.

This feature request can be split into two parts - a flag set on the queue that specifies that the owner should not be contacted, and a system to automatically assign a ticket to a person, but only when that ticket is generated by an email queue. AFAIK this 2nd feature is **not** the same as default_owner - default_owner only assigns an owner when an anonymous user creates a ticket via the web page.

Any comments?
",{},{}
